h3. Summary

New editor fails to publish a page if its content contains ASCII's control character.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Copy and paste a text containing control character such as backspace (\b).
# Try to save the page


h3. Expected Results

Editor saves printable characters.

h3. Actual Results

Editor complains an error saying "Unable to communicate with server. Saving is not possible at the moment.".

Response from the server:

{code:javascript}
{"statusCode":500,"message":"com.ctc.wstx.exc.WstxLazyException: [com.ctc.wstx.exc.WstxLazyException] Illegal character ((CTRL-CHAR, code 8))\n at [row,col {unknown-source}]: [67,500]"}
{code}

h3. Workaround

Copy all the content in an affected page and paste it to a text file. Then grep the file to find the problematic character.
{code:none}
$ cat ~/memo.txt | grep $'\b'
{code}

Also consider adding yourself as a watcher to be kept informed as to the state of the bug moving forward. With that way, if our development team updates the ticket, you'll be notified via email.

h3. Issue Summary

When performing a search after a page title, we have noticed that there are two links returned, one is the correct page link, but there is also a second page link which returns a Page Not found error. This issue only happened during migration from server to cloud, and only when the users migrated their site/space twice. The first import is a test run, so users deleted the spaces for the first import, they imported the space again, and the search results now contain deleted page links from the first import.
h3. Environment

Atlassian Cloud
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Import a Confluence space with multiple pages as a test 
 # Delete the space
 # Import again the space
 # Search after a page title
 # Notice that two links are displayed

h3. Expected Results

Search should return only relevant page links, not the deleted page links
h3. Actual Results

The search results contains also cache deleted pages from previous imports.
h3. Notes

We have noticed that even if we run a Content indexing and Clear cache for the site, the issue still persists.
h3. Workaround

Please contact support to open a request for CSRE. They have permission to run Elasticsearch query and update the sequence in the database
 * Run an Elasticsearch query to find out the max version in the index. Send POST query to {color:#505050}[http://|http:]{confluence_hostname}:9200/csp_\{confluence_shard_name}_confluence_2/_search. Body:{color}

{code:java}
{  
    "size":0,
    "query":{
      "term": {
        "tenantId": $tenant_Id
      }
    },
    "aggs" : {
        "max_version" : { "max" : { "field" : "_version" } }
    }
}{code}
 * Bump the document_version_seq to max version in the index + 1. For example, if the max _version field in the index is 4301, then we will need to update the document_version_seq to version 4302
 * 
{code:java}
SELECT last_value FROM document_version_seq;
{code}

 * 
{code:java}
SELECT setval('document_version_seq', 111, true);
{code}

 * Run re-index again.

 
